      "\n         `vₚ(xⁿ - yⁿ) = vₚ(x - y) + vₚ(n)`.\n       - In this case, if we set `x = 2`, `y = -1`, and `n = 3ᵏ`, then:\n         `x - y = 2 - (-1) = 3`, so `v₃(x - y) = 1`.\n         `xⁿ - yⁿ = 2^{3ᵏ} - (-1)^{3ᵏ} = 2^{3ᵏ} + 1`.\n         So `v₃(2^{3ᵏ} + 1) = v₃(2 - (-1)) + v₃(3ᵏ) = 1 + k = k + 1`.\n       - Thus, `3^{k+1} ∣ 2^{3ᵏ} + 1`, but `3^{k+1}` does not divide it?\n         No, it gives `v₃(2^{3ᵏ} + 1) = k + 1`, meaning `2^{3ᵏ} + 1` is divisible by `3^{k+1}`. Wait, no: LTE gives `v₃(2^{3ᵏ} + 1) = 1 + k`, so in fact it should be divisible by `3^{k+1}` (for `k ≥ 1`, `3^{k+1}` divides `2^{3ᵏ} + 1`). But our previous calculation for `k = 1` gave `2³ + 1 = 9 = 3²`, `v₃ = 2 = 1 + 1`. Correct. For `k = 2`, `2⁹ + 1 = 513 = 3³ * 19`, `v₃ = 3 = 1 + 2`. Correct. So LTE seems to prove that `3ᵏ⁺¹ ∣ 2^{3ᵏ} + 1`.\n       - This means that `3ᵏ⁺¹` divides `2^{3ᵏ} + 1`. But we wanted that `3ᵏ` divides `2^{3ᵏ} + 1`, which is even better (`k + 1 > k`). So actually `3ᵏ` divides `2^{3ᵏ} + 1` for all `k ≥ 1`, and furthermore, `3^{k+1}` divides it for all `k ≥ 1`.\n\n   - However, I think there was a misapplication of LTE. Let's try to recall LTE correctly:\n     - The correct statement of LTE for `p = 3`, `x = 2`, `y = -1` (`p` odd, `p ∤ x`, `p ∤ y`, `p ∣ x - y`):\n       - `v₃(2ⁿ - (-1)ⁿ) = v₃(2 - (-1)) + v₃(n)` for `n ≥ 1`.\n       - So here `xⁿ - yⁿ = 2ⁿ - (-1)ⁿ = 2ⁿ + 1` if `n` is odd.\n       - Thus, for `n = 3ᵏ`, which is odd, `v₃(2^{3ᵏ} + 1) = v₃(3) + v₃(3ᵏ) = 1 + k = k + 1`.\n       - Therefore, `v₃(2^{3ᵏ} + 1) = k + 1`, which means `3^{k+1}` divides `2^{3ᵏ} + 1`, but",
