3. **Chinese Remainder Theorem Approach**: To have `n` divide `2ⁿ + 1`, it is necessary that for every prime `p` dividing `n`, `2ⁿ ≡ -1 mod p`. But `n` is a multiple of `p`, so `2ⁿ ≡ (2ᵖ)ᵏ ≡ 1ᵏ ≡ 1 mod p` if `p` does not divide `2` (i.e., `p` is odd). Then `1 ≡ -1 mod p`, which means `p` divides `2`. So the only possibility is `p = 2`, but then `n` is even and `2ⁿ ≡ 0 mod 2`, so `2ⁿ + 1 ≡ 1 mod 2`, but `n` is even and thus `n ≡ 0 mod 2`, so `n` cannot divide `2ⁿ + 1`. 

